                      <item xml:id="e2">
                        <locus target="#24v #40v #50v #148r" facs="027 043 053 150">Fols. 24v, 40v, 50v, 148r</locus>
                        <desc>and lines of text are written interlinearly</desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e3">
                        <locus target="#131v" facs="134">Fol. 131v</locus>
                        <desc>erasure markings are visible</desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e4">
                        <locus target="#3v #5v #25r #90r" facs="006 008 027 092">Fols. 3v, 5v, 25r, 90r</locus>
                        <desc>e.g., text has been removed</desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e5">
                        <locus target="#61r #87r #90v" facs="063 089 093">Fols. 61r, 87r, 90v</locus>
                      <desc>e.g., the scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate
                      aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe completes the line
                      of text above or below the end of the line (throughout). This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the
                      next line</desc>
                      </item>

                    </list>
